
Command Descriptions (Ubuntu / lnav Usage)

1. sudo apt update

Updates the local package lists from configured repositories.
This ensures your system knows about the latest available packages and versions.



2. sudo apt install lnav -y

Installs "lnav" (Log File Navigator).

 "-y" automatically answers “yes” to install prompts.
  lnav is a powerful CLI tool for viewing and filtering logs.



3. lnav --version

Displays the installed version of "lnav".
Useful for verifying the installation and included in scripts for debugging or compatibility checks.



4. /mnt/d/sanitized_log

This refers to a directory path on the mounted Windows drive (WSL).
"/mnt/d/" is how WSL mounts the D: drive.
"sanitized_log" is most likely a folder containing log files.



5. ls /mnt/d/sanitized_log

Lists all files in the "sanitized_log" directory.
Commonly used to verify the available log files before opening them in lnav.



6. lnav /mnt/d/sanitized_log/

Opens "lnav" and loads all log files inside the specified directory.
lnav automatically detects formats (syslog, apache, auth logs, etc.) and indexes them.



 lnav Filter Commands

When inside the lnav interface, these filters refine which log entries are displayed.



7.filter-in sshd.*segfault

Displays only log lines that match the regex:
"sshd.*segfault"
Meaning: show logs where the SSH daemon (`sshd`) experienced or referenced a **segmentation fault**.

Use case: debugging SSH crashes or exploitation attempts.



8. filter-in accepted password

Shows only log entries that contain the phrase "accepted password".

Used to identify successful SSH login attempts.



9. filter-in su:.*root

Filters logs containing events where the "su" command was used to switch to the "root user".

"su:.*root" = any log line starting with `su:` and mentioning `root`.

Useful for privilege escalation auditing.



10. filter-in php

Shows only log entries containing the string "php".
Used for debugging PHP applications or checking for PHP-related errors/attacks.



11. filter-in invalid user

Displays log entries containing "invalid user".
This appears in "/var/log/auth.log" when someone attempts SSH login using a non-existent username.

Useful for identifying brute-force attempts or suspicious login activity.

